node.text:
🍎APPLE TRACING🍏🎨 A Back-to-School and apple themed prewriting activity for your little ones to enjoy as we approach back to school season 🤗👉 Use a sharpie to draw some 🍎 outlines on paper or cardboard. Supply red, green and yellow paints + Q-tips for tracing the lines of each apple. We went through and traced each outline, and then the color words inside. 🖍 ••••••• Will you save this simple activity and fine motor practice to try with your little ones ?! 👇 Share with a momma or teacher friend in comments below ❤️ Happy Sunday!
.
.
.
.

node.text:
20 SIMPLE SENSORY BINS 🖐🏿🖐🏽🖐🏻 to entertain the little ones! • Save this list of easy sensory play combos - it’s a great place to start if you’re new to sensory bins and a great place to refer back to if you’re blanking and in need of a quick setup for your littles! ❤️•••• Why sensory bins?! First of all, I find that a sensory bin is usually always worth the time it takes to set up because my kids are entertained by them the longest. I can sit back and watch all the learning taking place as they explore the new materials with their senses and continue to develop important fine motor and life skills through scooping, pouring, etc. Hands on learning & independent playtime for your littles? Yes please! ••••••• There are so many benefits to sensory bin play time for our toddlers and preschoolers- share with a momma friend who might love this list of inspo as well! ❤️👇 Happy Wednesday!!
.
.
.
.
.
.

node.text:
🧐MISSING LETTER WORDS ✏️• I love this one for big kids! First, I rolled out a sheet of paper, collected some toys around the house, and wrote out each object word on the page with letter(s) missing from each. 👉👉 My little one’s job was then to complete the spelling for each word by sounding it out and filling in the missing letter. This was a great way to switch things up and get him thinking in a whole new way about some of the words he’s been reading and writing. ✍️ Tap to save it with the flag below🔖😉 Will you try at home?!
.
.
.
.
.

node.text:
🤩2 EASY PAPER PLATE CLAW CRAFTS 🦖 🐻• 👉Swipe and bookmark this post for two cute ideas that your kiddos will be excited about! 🔖••••••• Two paper plates with the bottom 1/4th cut off can be glued together around the edges and perfectly fit a little hand inside! We have made this craft into a dino claw as shown and also made adorable bear paws! •••••• TO MAKE CLAWS/PAWS: 1. Cut the bottom 1/4th off of two paper plates 2. Paint and decorate the bottom of the plates. 3. Glue plates together around edges of the top sides 4. Add construction paper cutout claws! 🐻🦖🤚5. Slip onto little hands and RAWRRR!! •••••••••••• Will you make these cuties with your Dino or animal fans at home? 
.
.
.
.
.

node.text:
🦒FEED THE ANIMALS Sensory Play 🦓 You’ll need two trays, boxes or storage bins for this simple sensory activity. Fill one side with small bowls and toy animals. Fill the other with a dry sensory material such as dry beans as shown (oats and rice are also fun). Add scooping tools and encourage your little ones to “feed the animals”! Lots of imaginative play come along with this sensory and fine motor activity. Will you try it at home with your preschoolers?! Let me know in comments and share with a friend who might love it as well 🥰👇
.
.
.
.
.

node.text: 🤩PLAYING CARD MATCHUP 🎴 🌈Need a screen-free way to kick off the morning with little ones?! Use your deck of cards or UNO card game for this simple setup. Color matching, counting and number recognition all in one fun game for preschoolers. Share with momma friends and let me know in comments today if you’ll try it! —- #preschoolathome #momblog #momlife #kidsactivities #montessori #kidscrafts #toddleractivities #toddlersofinstagram #teachermom #homeschool
